  "nursesNote": "ADHD is a childhood-onset disorder of inattention, hyperactivity, and impulsivity. Stimulants such as methylphenidate or amphetamine are first-line and work well, but the nurse times them in the morning and not in the late afternoon to prevent insomnia, gives them after meals to reduce appetite loss, and monitors growth, weight, and appetite along with heart rate and blood pressure. A non-stimulant such as atomoxetine is an option. Behavioral care uses a consistent routine, clear and simple expectations, fewer distractions, short tasks broken into steps, and praise for success; the nurse teaches the family and supports a school plan.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Give stimulants in the morning, not late afternoon",
    "Give stimulants after meals and monitor appetite and growth",
    "Monitor heart rate and blood pressure",
    "Use a consistent routine with clear, simple expectations",
    "Teach the family and support a school plan"
  ],
